Extraction elevation values from DEM¶

Introduction¶

In this 21st Century, depending on the accuracy, level of urgency, or measure of your integrity, there are two ways of collecting elevation values from any point on the Earth's surface. One is to go the field, and like a true surveyor collect the GPS points with a GPS handheld device or a smartphone. Most GPS handlheld devices and GPS apps collect both Lon-Lat coordinates with their corresponding altitudes. If you are the lazy type, are allergic to fieldwork or are severely limited in time and money to explore, looking for a DEM dataset online is very much welcome. For today, we shall concentrate on extracting elevation values at specific GPS coordinates all in python. Well, almost.

Load the DEM¶

First things first. We will have to load the Digital Elevation Model (DEM). DEMs come in various formats. In our very few years on this planet we have mostly come acros .tif, .hdr and .adf formats. Howver, .tif formats are the most common and easiest to work with. You'd probably need to check your GIS and Remote Sensing experience if you are yet to come across .tif somewhere. Anyway, we were talking about accessing the DEM. They also vary in terms of resolution. A DEM of 20m resolution is more accurate than that of 100m resolution. In our case, the DEM that beats many in their game is the ALOS PALSAR DEM that has a spatial resolution of 12.5m. We know there are more that are sharper than this, but they don't come cheap. The ALOS PALSAR datasets are available from ASF Alaska website. This article will not go into the details of accessing it, but this You Tube video saves us a lot of words .

We have also provided the shapefile we used as the Area of Interest (AOI) boundary, it is here.

After downloading the DEM, we will clip it to our AOI. In case you are lost in the ocean of resource of ASF Alaska website, we have gone the extra mile of downloading the DEM for you. Uncle Sam (the writer, not USA) cares after all. For the tough ones who don't mind the Alaskan web jungle, look for the file name AP_09915_FBS_F7150_RT1 from the raster files list.

We had also mentioned clipping in addition to acquiring the DEM. As oft mentioned, in remote sensing and even in programming it is better to work with bits rather than the entire bite. Working with the focus area saves time, prevents confusion and is friendly to your finite computer resources. But we are jumping ahead of the gun, let's first open the zip folder of our DEM.

Clip the DEM¶

Now is the time to clip our DEM. We will first load in the necessary packages for dealing with geospatial data. We have hashed the package names because in programming, it is good practice to call all your necessary packages at the top, rather than within the file. That is one mark of a polished programmer. But just for today we break the rules for your sake. Tomorrow we shall have the 'professional' coat back on.

In [5]:

Just as we cannot surgically operate on ourselves, so DEM files cannot clip themselves. We will use the same shapefile that you used to search for the DEM in the ASF Alaska website for clipping. Let's call it from our directory.

In [6]:
# Shapefile for clipping
shapefile_path = os.path.join(path, 'bounding.shp')

If you have worked in Qgis before, you know clipping a DEM is darn straightforward. But in Python, it's a long and scary process. We also confess we stood on the shoulders of giants to do it ourselves. We used this methodology from Stack Overflow.

Let's get on with it.

First open and extract the geometry of the shapefile.

In [7]:
with fiona.open(shapefile_path, "r") as shapefile:  # Open the shapefile from the path given
    shapes = [feature["geometry"] for feature in shapefile]  # a list comprehension for loop that means for every feature in the shapefile (if 
    # composed of many features) extract the geometry

Now let's open the raster DEM, and clip it to our shapefile bounds using the rasterio.mask function.

In [8]:
with rasterio.open(dem_path) as elev_dem:   # Open the raster

    out_image, out_transform = rasterio.mask.mask(elev_dem, shapes, crop=True)  # Mask out the raster
    out_meta = elev_dem.meta       # Assign the metadata of the clipped raster to the variable 'out_meta'

Update the metadata of the clipped DEM¶

After clipping, of course the metadata will not remain the same. It too must reflect the changes.

In [9]:
# Update metadata
out_meta.update({"driver": "GTiff",
                 "height": out_image.shape[1], # Assign the height values of the clipped image to metadata using the shape method??
                 "width": out_image.shape[2],  # Assign the width values of the clipped image to metadata using the shape method??
                 "transform": out_transform})

After clipping, it's good to have a copy of our clipped DEM. The following code will save it to our specified directory.

In [10]:
# Save raster image to directory
with rasterio.open(os.path.join(path, 'dem_files', 'clipped_dem.tif'), "w", **out_meta) as dest:
    dest.write(out_image)

However, we found it too challenging and prone to countless errors. Since we did the hardwork for you, we don't want you to repeat the same wild goose chase. There is a caveat, though, in using cartopy to display, as per an example we followed here, the points have to be in shapefile format. So that gives us an extra workload, converting the geodataframe to a shapefile. But it's a sigh of relief.

Extracting elevation values from the DEM¶

Tired already? Yes of course. But luckily this is the last bit. We will create a for loop to access the altitudes at specific Lon-Lat coordinates on the DEM. We will first create a new column elevation and assign it the default value 0. Any elevation values at our specific GPS points will be imputed to this default 0 value. Think of this logic as analogous to conducting a census using a Computerized Personal Assistant (CAPI), a tablet in this case. Every house within your jurisdiction has been assigned the value 0 in the tablet's census app. However, once you start conducting the census, you will change the value of each household in the tablet from 0 to the number of the members of each sampled household. Some households will have five members, others 10, others three, others 15 and so on... It's the same we are doing to our shapefile... imputing altitude values to each Lon-Lat coordinate we come across in the table from their corresponding position in the DEM.

One more caveat. The topography raster above did not do well in our function. It actually resulted in an error, by which we are now used to. But if we load the raster with our initial rasterio.open(), the for loop works magnificently. Do try to find out and see. Anyway, we work with what works so we christened our reproject raster as clipped_dem_rpj.

In [20]:
# Call the reprojected raster using rasterio package
clipped_dem_rpj = rasterio.open("E:/documents/gis800_articles/jupyter/terrain_dem/dem_files/clipped_dem_rpj.tif")

# For loop to extract elevation values
shapefile['elevation'] = 0

for index, row in shapefile.iterrows():
    # Extracting attributes
    name = row['Descriptio']
    latitude = row['geometry'].y
    longitude = row['geometry'].x
    
    # DEM
    row, col = clipped_dem_rpj.index(longitude, latitude)
    dem_data = clipped_dem_rpj.read(1)
    
    print(f"Name: {name}, \tElevation (m): {dem_data[row, col]}")
    
    # 
    shapefile['elevation'].loc[index] = dem_data[row, col]

Works like magic. If this is all you wanted, you can end here. However, since being a good programmer means you avoid redundancy, we will create a function that mimics the above for loop.

In [22]:
# Function to extract elevation values of a DEM using a shapefile (works for all .tifs and shapefiles

def createElevationColumn(shapefile: '.sh', dem:'.tif', column_name: 'str', geometry_column: 'str')->'gpd.GeoDataFrame':
    """This function is to create a new column called Elevation that consists of height values from the point positions on the dem
    Parameters:
    
    shapefile (.shp): A shapefile in the same projection as the reprojected raster
    dem (.tif): A Digital Elevation Model. This function works well with .tif format
    column_name ('str'): Write the column name in which you would like to associate your elevation values with eg. station names. Insert the column name in quotes (' ')
    geometry_column ('str'): The column name containing the Longitude_Latitude values (in that order). Must be a geometry column. Insert the name of this column in quotes (' ') like in column_name.
    
    Returns:
    gpd.GeoDataFrame: The result is a geoDataFrame with elevation values at Lon-Lat coordinates of each particular point (row) extracted from the DEM
    """
    shapefile['elevation'] = 0
    for index, row in shapefile.iterrows():
        name=row[column_name]
        longitude = row[geometry_column].x
        latitude = row[geometry_column].y
        
        row, col = dem.index(longitude, latitude)
        dem_data = dem.read(1)
        
        print(f"Name: {name}, \tElevation (m): {dem_data[row, col]}")
        
        
        shapefile['elevation'].loc[index] = dem_data[row, col]

Conclusion¶

Digital Elevation Models (DEMs) have made our GIS work easier in that one doesn't have to go to the field to extract elevation values. In today's exercise, we saw how to plot a raster and a vector in one image, although it is far from sounding simple. We also used a for loop to extract the elevation values for each GPS point, and subsequently created a function for this task which can be replicated for any shapefile and raster.
